grant-rich environments, in work, school, public interactions, romantic life, and leisure activities. With lucid prose, Jiménez reveals how immigration not only changes the American cityscape but also reshapes the United States by altering the outlooks and identities of its most established citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAssimilation (Sociology)zCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County) 0aAssimilation (Sociology)zCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aCity dwellersxCultural assimilationzCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County) 0aCity dwellersxCultural assimilationzCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aImmigrantszCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County) 0aImmigrantszCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  adaca.  aestablished citizens.  aestablished immigrants.  ahuman rights advocate.  aimmigrant-rich environment.  aimmigration studies.  ainfluence of immigrants.  anationalism.  apolitical science major.  asilicon valley.  aus immigrant relations.  axenophobia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029569840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096837040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968370423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520968370/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles